post_text:
This week wraps up a series of school tours we’ve been hosting with School Board members and division leadership to evaluate each schools reopening plans. We’re so proud of the hard work by every staff member involved in making this happen. Each school has a great plan in place and they are eager to welcome staff and students back for the new school year. While each schools individual plan may vary slightly, the overall goal remains the same - prepare a space ready for students and staff to return to learn in a safe environment while taking every precaution possible to effectively run all of the logistics encompassing the school day.

For a glimpse into what this entails, see today’s The Winchester Star for an inside look at Daniel Morgan Middle School’s reopening plan.

To view the full scope of our Return to Learn plans and all associated resources and information, please visit: https://www.wps.k12.va.us/ReturntoLearn

post_text: Summer Meal Distribution Reminder -- The last day of summer meal deliveries at our city locations will be tomorrow, August 18th. We will resume meal delivery to children on our first day of school, September 8th. This short break gives our cafeterias time to plan menus, organize our workforce, order supplies, and get ready for school opening. For this school year, if you attend school on the hybrid plan, you will be provided meals at your assigned school on your assigned day. If you are distance learning, we will make meals available for pickup at your assigned school. We will have more information in the coming weeks regarding our procedures for meal pickup. Stay safe!

post_text:
On Monday evening the School Board unanimously approved a memorandum of agreement (MOA) with Winchester City Council moving us another step forward in the process of renovating the historic Douglas School.

In general the MOA requests that WPS be approved to use carry over funds from this year's operating budget (primarily as a result of savings incurred from the extended school closure) toward the project. In addition, once the project is complete and the transition has occurred WPS would be guaranteed a minimum return of $1.5 million from the future sale of the current office property, allowing us to rebuild our capital fund.

For additional details see today’s The Winchester Star or review Monday evenings school board report on our website.

Virginia High School League
July 27 at 10:39 AM ·

Fall Update

This morning, the VHSL Executive Committee voted to approve Model 3 in the re-opening of high school sports and activities. This model delays sports and activities until December 14 and keeps all sports in the seasons where they are currently aligned.

Model 3 adopts the Condensed Interscholastic Plan: (shown below)

We would like to thank everyone for their understanding and support. We would also like to thank the VHSL Executive Committee and athletic administrators for their work. The health and safety of student athletes remains our main priority as we move towards a season.

We will keep you all informed as new details become available.

shared_text:
VMDO Architects
May 27 at 12:28 PM ·

"This facility is needed so much now," shares a Winchester, VA community member upon seeing the design of the Shihadeh Innovation Center take shape for Winchester Public Schools. "We need to create spaces for innovation and project-based learning to support new tradespeople! I can hardly wait to see this project fully completed and in use." A joint venture with Lord Fairfax Community College and local industry partners, the Shihadeh Innovation Center will be a hub of workforce development for the community – preparing both Winchester high school students and community members to meet the demands of the regional job market. All high school students will have an opportunity to apply their academic knowledge to practical skills while adults and professionals can learn a new trade to re-enter the workforce or mentor youth interested in their field. Designed by VMDO and partners Reader & Swartz Architects, the building breathes new life into a former elementary school and is on track to open in spring 2021.

REMINDER - The end of school year student chromebook collection will be different this year. Seniors will return their chromebooks (as well as cases, chargers, calculators, textbooks, library books, and any other school property) on May 26 and May 27 from 10:00 am - 12:30 pm. Enter Handley Blvd and proceed to the Handley Circle. Please come prepared to pay for any missing or damaged items.

We will not be collecting chromebooks at the end of the school year for students in grades 3-11. Instead, students will keep their chromebooks over the summer and must return them on the first day of the 2020-2021 school year. It is important to take good care of the chromebooks and not lose them. Any student who will be moving over the summer or not returning to WPS for the 2020-2021 school year must contact their school to arrange to return the chromebook.

We hope that students will appreciate having access to technology to continue distance learning opportunities over the summer.

Winchester Public Schools and John Handley High School are so proud of Bich Ngoe Vo for being awarded the Carnation Care Award for Extraordinary Nursing Assistants from Valley Health as she works as a Certified Nurse Aide as part of the cooperative education program collaboration between Winchester Medical Center and Winchester Public Schools.

Bich completed the JHHS Nurse Aide program in the spring of 2019 and has been working at Valley Health in the capacity of a Nurse Aide over the 2019-2020 school year. The honor of this recognition is open for all Nursing Assistants and other healthcare technicians employed at Valley Health.

The Carnation nomination is made by a patient who has received exceptional care during an experience at Winchester Medical Center. The patient states:

“I am impressed with this young lady’s care and dedication to her job. I am amazed at the meticulous care she took…to do so with such concern for my comfort…she went above and beyond to help me. It’s rewarding to see someone that young show so much care for someone under her care.”

The support center is located in the Central Administration Office at 12 N Washington St. Please enter the parking lot behind the building and look for the signs (garage door entrance at back of building).

Technology staff will be onsite during these times to troubleshoot and repair WPS issued devices, including chromebooks, for students and staff. Phone support is also available during these hours at 540-667-4253 ext: 10200. #gowps #StrongerTogetherWPS

post_text:
If you received a BRIGHTfutures food bag at your home two weeks ago, or have turned in forms to receive a bag since then, you must pick up their food packs this Thursday, April 2 from 11:00 am - 1:00 pm at Daniel Morgan Middle School, Garland R. Quarles Elementary School, Frederick Douglass Elementary School or Virginia Avenue Elementary School.

Food packs will not be delivered to homes. We ask that those picking up the food packs practice social distancing. If you are walking to pick up your food bags you may want to consider bringing a stroller or wagon to help carry them home.

If you have any questions about the food pack program or this weeks food pack pickup, please contact Judy McKiernan at 540.974.4104.

post_text: Shout out to Winchester Police Department for an exciting new program they are launching for children (10 and under) who will be missing out on fun birthday activities in the next couple of months - watch the video (sound on!) for details!
shared_text:
Winchester Police Department
March 26 at 2:51 PM ·

We 💙 our community. And we miss seeing all of you at our usual community outreach events. We have an exciting new program that we're beginning to bring joy to our youngest residents (10 and under) who will be missing out on fun birthday activities in the next couple of months - watch the video (sound on!) for details!

Parents, if you:
🥳 Are a resident of the City of Winchester (ZIP 22601) and...
🎂 Have a child that is ten years old or younger who...
🎈Has a birthday in April or May, then...
contact Lt. Amanda Behan to arrange a special, personalized birthday wish from a Winchester Police Officer at your home (social distancing compliant) for your child!

👝 amanda.behan@winchesterva.gov
📞540-545-4716

Donations can be dropped off at the BRIGHTfutures Distribution Center located at 178 Indian Hollow Road at any time and should be placed in the bins located at the entrance of the center.

post_text: The educator, the coach, the legend...Tommy Dixon
shared_text:
WPS Equity & Community Engagement
February 16 at 8:00 AM ·

Thomas "Tommy" Dixon is from Winchester, VA and a beloved Coach and Educator of Winchester Public Schools.

As a Head Basketball Coach, Coach Dixon racked up a total of 405 wins during his 32 years at Handley and was also the first African American coach for Winchester Public Schools.

Dixon's career as an educator spanned decades. As result of his love for his students, athletes, and community, Dixon made an indelible mark on many lives.

In 2016, the basketball court at John Handley High School was named after Coach Tommy Dixon to cement his outstanding career.

Coach Dixon was also inducted into the Judges Athletic Association Hall of Fame in 2001 and the Potomac State College Hall of Fame in 2010.
#BlackHistoryMonth2020
#Excellence

We're really enjoying the local history lesson each day in celebration of Black History Month as we learn more about prominent individuals with ties to Winchester and the surrounding area who have made incredible impact locally and beyond.

Check in each day of February at WPS Equity & Inclusion to see who will be featured next. #gowps #BlackHistoryMonth2020
shared_text:
WPS Equity & Community Engagement
February 10 at 8:27 AM ·

Kara Dixon is from Winchester, VA and a graduate of John Handley High School.

Kara is a graduate of the University of Maryland’s Philip Merrill College of Journalism.

At UMD, she participated in the CBC-UNC Diversity Fellowship Program led by UNC and WRAL.

During college, Kara was a member of Capital News Service and ViewFinder presented by the University of Maryland. Both programs won numerous regional and national awards.

She spent two years as a multimedia journalist at KFDM/KBTV in Beaumont, Texas, where she covered everything from historic flooding to crime.

Currently, Kara is a journalist and reporter for WAVY in the Hampton Roads area where she is also the host of “Candid with Kara.”

Kara is the daughter of Legendary Coach Tommy Dixon and Long-Time Winchester Public Schools Educator/ Local Historian, Sharon Dixon.
#BlackHistoryMonth2020
#Excellence

post_text:
Our ASPIRE program is designed to bridge the summer for students who have fallen behind in their pursuit of a high school diploma. However, instead of a traditional summer school, the ASPIRE program also seeks to engage students in our community and in the real world of work and service. The ASPIRE program hopes to empower students to embrace their future in a positive way and connect the value of school to their future lives.

#gowps #handleypride

Virginia's Department of Education, local school division's and key partner organizations and working together to refresh a commitment to ensure that students are ready to thrive after graduation.

The "Virginia is for Learners" commitment focuses on several key components including: new standards of accreditation for Virginia schools, an increased emphasis on early childhood education, modernizing the Virginia standards of learning, new high school graduation requirements and career pathways, a stronger focus on deeper learning, and maximizing the potential of all students.

To learn more about the Virginia is for Learners commitment, please visit: www.VirginiaIsForLearners.Virginia.Gov

For the next two weeks beginning tomorrow, Monday, April 1, Winchester Public Schools will be partnering with Panorama Education to host a School Quality and Climate Survey. Your feedback is essential as our schools work to create the school and classroom environments students and staff deserve.

Parents, look for your survey link via email invitation or you may access the link from our school or district websites. You may also stop by any school’s front office and take the survey online.

Staff, look for your survey link via email invitation from Panorama. Students will be provided their access information during class.

All responses are anonymous and confidential. We appreciate your participation.

For more details visit: https://bit.ly/2HWp0FZ

Did you know that WPS has the capacity to serve 144 preschool students at 200% of the poverty level or below in our full day program in our elementary schools?

For more information about our preschool program, including how to apply please visit: www.wps.k12.va.us/preschool

post_text:
Congratulations to John Handley High School senior Taylor Beard on recently winning both the High Jump and the Triple Jump at the VHSL Class 4 Indoor Track Championships.

Beard, who also was an All Region basketball selection this winter, won the High Jump with a jump of 5'9" (breaking the record she set last year) and won the Triple Jump with a jump of 38'2".

Earlier this year, Beard signed a National Letter of Intent to accept a full track scholarship at the University of Cincinnati.

#gowps #handleypride
